intro.goal: The goal of this game is to guess a Minecraft block. Every day a new block is chosen, and by continuing to guess the block of the day, you can build up a win-streak!
intro.enter_guesses: Begin by typing the name of any block in the search field. Based on your search, up to 10 results will pop up. Click on any of these blocks, or navigate to them with your arrow keys and press Enter to lock your guess in.
intro.field_explanation: The properties of your chosen block will be compared to today's block and will be marked green if matching, yellow for partial matches, and red if incorrect. Behind incorrect number/version fields, you will also find an arrow indicating whether you should guess higher or lower.

example.title: Example
example.intro: Let's look at an example game. First we'll try an arbitrary block.
example.table_interpretation_1: We've learned that the block, like most others, is stackable until 64, and it is not flammable. It was not added in the versions pre-alpha and can't be mined with a Pickaxe. So let's try a different, newer, block.
example.table_interpretation_2: We've discovered the block's version! Time to look for a block added in Beta 1.8. Additionally, we got a partial match on the tool, so it can be broken by an Axe and some other tool. Also, the block is neither transparent ("Yes") nor non-transparent ("No"), so it must be partially transparent. Let's look for a block that matches all of these properties.
example.table_interpretation_3: There we go! We've discovered that the block was a block of melon, what a delight!

partial_matches.title: Partial Match explanation
partial_matches.intro: Let's look at partial matches in detail, 'cause these are probably the most confusing of the tile colors.
partial_matches.explanation: A partial match can only appear in fields that consist of a list (e.g. Tools). If you guessed a block that can be broken with at least one tool that matches the actual block, you will get a partial match. Here's an example for leaves:

tips.title: Tips
tips.not_all_blocks: MCdle does not contain every type of block. All the colored variants of concrete, terracotta, wool, etc. are merged into one representative block like "Concrete" or "Wool". This also applies to the different wood types, walls, stairs, etc.
tips.utilize_the_search: Make good use of the search bar! Looking through the suggestions will help you narrow down your search.
tips.use_the_wiki: Feel free to use the Minecraft wiki. As soon as you've determined the version of the block, you can use the wiki to find the blocks that were added in that version, which will help you narrow down your search drastically.

intro.goal: The goal of this game is to guess a Minecraft item. Every day a new item is chosen, and by continuing to guess the item of the day, you can build up a win-streak.
intro.enter_guesses: Begin by typing the name of any item in the search field. Based on your search, up to 10 results will pop up. Click on any of these items, or navigate to them with your arrow keys and press Enter to lock your guess in.
intro.field_explanation: The properties of your chosen item will be compared to today's item and will be marked green if matching, yellow for partial matches, and red if incorrect. Behind incorrect number/version fields, you will also find an arrow indicating whether you should guess higher or lower.

example.title: Example
example.intro: Let's look at an example game. First we'll try an arbitrary item.
example.table_interpretation_1: We've learned that the item, like most others, is stackable until 64. It's newer than Beta 1.2, has Common rarity, is renewable, and there are less than 5 ways how to use it, and less than 6 ways to obtain it, according to the Minecraft wiki. It's inventory category tells us that we are not looking for a Item in the "Ingredient" category. Let's try a different item.
example.table_interpretation_2: We've discovered the items version! Time to look for an item added in Beta 1.8 that's in the "Food & Drinks" creative inventory category. We now need to look for an item with matching use cases and methods of obtaining.
example.table_interpretation_3: There we go! We've discovered that the item was a melon slice, what a joy!

partial_matches.title: Partial Match explanation
partial_matches.intro: Let's look at partial matches in detail, 'cause these are probably the most confusing of the tile colors.
partial_matches.explanation: A partial match can only appear in fields that consist of a list (e.g. the inventory category). If you guessed an item that is in at least one inventory category that matches the actual item, you will get a partial match. Here's an example for string:

tips.title: Tips
tips.not_all_items: MCdle does not contain every type of item. The list is taken from the Minecraft wiki and hence does not contain the item forms of various blocks or too similar items, like all the armor/tool variants.
tips.utilize_the_search: Make good use of the search bar! Looking through the suggestions will help you narrow down your search.
tips.use_the_wiki: Feel free to use the Minecraft wiki. As soon as you've determined the version of the item, you can use the wiki to find the items that were added in that version, which will help you narrow down your search drastically.
tips.usage_and_source_explanation: If you are curious how the Usage count/Source count is calculated, check the item's wiki page and scroll to "Obtaining" and "Usage". The headers of these sections have been used to count their different usecases. If they were missing, I, the developer, have added them manually.

intro.goal: The goal of this game is to guess a Minecraft mob. Every day a new mob is chosen, and by continuing to guess the mob of the day, you can build up a win-streak.
intro.enter_guesses: Begin by typing the name of any mob in the search field. Based on your search, up to 10 results will pop up. Click on any of these mobs, or navigate to them with your arrow keys and press Enter to lock your guess in.
intro.field_explanation: The properties of your chosen mob will be compared to today's mob and will be marked green if matching, yellow for partial matches, and red if incorrect. Behind incorrect number/version fields, you will also find an arrow indicating whether you should guess higher or lower.

example.title: Example
example.intro: Let's look at an example game. First we'll try an arbitrary mob.
example.table_interpretation_1: From this guess, we can see that the mob we're looking for was added after version 1.6.1, doesn't have a lot of health, is less then 1.6 blocks tall, and might be passive, hostile, or a mix of the two. It's not summoned by lightning and it's not undead either.
example.table_interpretation_2: Alright, still newer than 1.13, but we got the health: we're looking for a mob with 10 HP, aka 5 hearts. It's less than 0.6 blocks tall, so we're looking for a small mob. The mob's behavior is still a partial match, so it's very likely passive, but could still be hostile & neutral. Both the spawn and classification fields got a partial match, so the mob's spawn origins would be biome and something else, and the mob would be classified as either animal, aquatic, and maybe something else in addition to one of these two possibilities.
example.table_interpretation_3: Let's go! Look who hopped into this tutorial. We've found a little frog!

partial_matches.title: Partial Match explanation
partial_matches.intro: Let's look at partial matches in detail, 'cause these are probably the most confusing of the tile colors.
partial_matches.explanation: A partial match can only appear in fields that consist of a list (e.g. the spawn, classification, or behavior fields). If you guessed a mob with at least one list element that matches the actual mob, you will get a partial match. Here's an example for horses:

tips.title: Tips
tips.not_all_blocks: MCdle does not contain every type of entity. Only living entities, like pigs or zombies, are included. Armor stands, projectiles, or similar non-living entities are not included. The list is taken from the Minecraft wiki, so if it's not on there in the mob list, it's not in this game.
tips.utilize_the_search: Make good use of the search bar! Looking through the suggestions will help you narrow down your search.
tips.use_the_wiki: Feel free to use the Minecraft wiki. As soon as you've determined the version of the mob, you can use the wiki to find the mobs that were added in that version, which will help you narrow down your search drastically.
tips.health_measuring: Keep in mind that health is measured in health points, aka half hearts, so 10 HP is 5 hearts.

intro.goal: The goal of this game is to craft as many items as possible with the 7 items provided in the hexagons. This gamemode has a daily mode, as well as an unlimited mode paired with an editor. By completing the daily mode, you can build up a win-streak. By playing unlimited, you get to learn how to play the game, recipes, and play riddles that other players created using the editor!
intro.entering_items: To begin playing, select an item in the hexagons and then click a slot in the crafting table grid, where clicking multiple slots will "paint" these slots. Repeat this process until you see your desired recipe in the output slot. Then, click the resulting item to craft! Alternatively, you can also drag-and-drop items from the hexagons or from one slot to another. Additionally, you could also be a "Keyboard Wizard" and select the hexagons with the number keys, WASD or arrow keys for the crafting table slots, Space to place, and Enter to craft. Keybinds can be configured in the settings located to the left of the MCdle title.

example.title: Example
example.intro: Let's look at some examples! From a single diamond, we can craft 5 individual items!
example.hint_info: Feeling stuck? You can enable hints in the box below the delete/clear buttons. The hints will appear above the individual hexagons and tell you how many items you have remaining to craft with that ingredient! From there, you can visit the

tips.title: Tips
tips.individual_results_only: The game only counts individual results, not individual recipes. For example, both bamboo and planks make sticks, but once you crafted sticks with either, that's it!
tips.where_help: Use the hint system if you are stuck. The wiki pairs well with it, just search for the item you are missing!
tips.not_all_recipes: Crafting Bee does not contain every craftable recipe. Only standard shaped and shapeless recipes inside the crafting table are included. Non standard recipes, like custom fireworks, decorated pots, or similar are not included.
